Okunâ€™s law and the US economy

Lovdip Singh

Question of interest/goal of the study

We want to investigate Okunâ€™s law using data from the US economy. That is, for every 1% decrease in unemployment rate there should be a corresponding 2% increase in GDP.

Read in and inspect the data:

okun.df=read.table("okun.txt", header=T)
plot(GDP~Unemp,xlab="% change in unemployment rate", ylab="% change in GDP",data=okun.df)

The relationship between the quarterly % change in unemplyement (explanatory variable) and the quarterly % change in GDP (response variable) appears to be a negative linear relationship. The variation appears to be constant.

Model fitting

okun.fit=lm(GDP~Unemp,data=okun.df)
plot(okun.fit,which=1)

normcheck(okun.fit)

cooks20x(okun.fit)

summary(okun.fit)

plot(GDP~Unemp,xlab="% change in unemployment rate", ylab="% change in GDP",data=okun.df)
abline(okun.fit, lty = 2, col = "blue")

Prediction for % change in GDP given the % change in unemployment for the final quarter of 2015

predict(okun.fit, newdata = data.frame(Unemp=100 * ((5-5.1) / 5.1)), interval = "prediction")
##        fit     lwr      upr
## 1 4.422683 2.91165 5.933717

Given the % change in unemployment for the final quarter of 2015 (-1.96%), the 95% prediction interval for quarterly change in GDP % was between 2.91% and 5.93%. This interval does not contatin the actual % change in GDP, which was 2%.

A -1.96% is an extremely high change in quarterly unemplyement rate, in our data set there were fewer data points at the negative extrema of % change in unemployment, with the largest decrease in employment being -0.967%. Therefore our model may not be a good predictor when using an extreme % change in unemployment rate. The linear model explained 50.24% of the variability, further reducing the precision of the predicted % change in GDP.

Method and Assumption Checks

The data follows a linear relationship, so we have fitted a simple linear regression model. There was some concerns with a hint of curvature in the residuals, but this was mostly at the extremes where there were quite sparse data so likely to have been the influenced by just a few points. (Fitting a curve is unlikely to be helpful for this data - any small gain in explanatory power will be heavily offset by the complication in the model.) Note - we are treating these observation as independent which is not correct as this is historical data which is related by time. (Any problems with time dependence can actually be checked for - see Time Series later in the course.) All other assumptions seem valid.

Our model is: \(GDP_i =\beta_0 +\beta_1\times Unemp_i +\epsilon_i\) where \(\epsilon_i \sim iid ~ N(0,\sigma^2)\)

Our model only explains about 50% of the variation in the data (so any predictions wonâ€™t be very precise).

Executive Summary

We were interested in finding the relationship between the quarterly change in GDP (%) and the quarterly change in unemployment rate (%) from a data set from USA. Furthermore, we wanted to see if this relationship conformed with Okunâ€™s Law, i.e.Â for every 1% decrease in unemployment rate there should be a corresponding 2% increase in GDP.

There was a clear linear relationship between % change in unemployment and % change in GDP (P-value â‰ˆ 0). We estimate that for a for each percentage point increase in quarterly unemployment rate, the quarterly GDP would decrease by -1.58% to -2.06% on average. This 95% confidence interval contains the the value -2% which conforms to okunâ€™s law, i.e a 1% point increase in unemployment rate corresponds to a 2% decrease in GDP, or alternatively, a 1% point decrease in unemployment rate corresponds to a 2% increase in GDP.
